properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Emerson, Letellier, Morris, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-11-02T15:00:00-05:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Total snowfall: 15 to 35 cm. Locations: Upper Lake Melville, Eagle River, Rigolet, inland areas near Cartwright. Time span: continuing until late tonight. Remarks: Snow, heavy at times, will continue tonight. In the Upper Lake Melville area, 25 to 35 cm of snow is expected. For Rigolet, inland areas near Cartwright, and Eagle River, snowfall accumulations of 15 to 25 cm can be expected. The snow will mix with or change to rain along parts of the coast from Cartwright to Black Tickle. In the Eagle River area, the snow will change to ice pellets this evening. Additionally, northeasterly winds gusting to 50 or 60 km/h will give blowing snow over exposed areas tonight. The snow will taper to flurries by Saturday morning. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Local significant snowfall amounts are possible tonight and Saturday. Flurries associated with a weak low pressure system will start this evening. Behind the low pressure system, with the cold west and northwest flow over relatively warm waters of Lake Superior, local snow squalls are also expected to develop late tonight and continuing into Saturday afternoon. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm with locally higher amounts over higher terrain are possible by Saturday evening. Driving conditions might become difficult due to accumulated snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels with large waves are expected near the coast. Warning of potential breaking sea conditions and overwash issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Region on 2019-10-31. An intense low pressure system arriving from the Great Lakes will cause strong to high winds over the regions listed below. The combination of these winds and the current run of high tidal ranges could produce breaking sea conditions along the coast near the following localities, on the dates and at the times specified (Eastern Daylight Time). Anticosti: 2019-11-01, from 3:30 P.M. to 7:00 P.M. Natashquan: 2019-11-01, from 01:00 PM to 04:30 PM. Chevery: 2019-11-01, from 01:00 PM to 04:30 PM. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. High waves combined with the surge may cause damage along the coast. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
